"""
MKT Original Commentary — 1 Samuel chapters 9–12
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1samuel-9-12.py

Ch 9: Saul sought and found — YHWH's providence through a donkey search leads to anointing.
Ch 10: The anointing, three confirming signs, the Spirit's coming, lot-selection at Mizpah.
Ch 11: Saul delivers Jabesh-Gilead; Spirit-empowered war; kingdom renewed at Gilgal.
Ch 12: Samuel's farewell covenant speech — YHWH's saving history, conditions, intercession pledge.

Key term decisions:
- nāgîd: "prince/leader" (not king — a different word from melek)
- ṣālaḥ: "rush upon" for Spirit coming (captures sudden, powerful onset)
- rōʾeh / nāḇîʾ: transliterated + explained (9:9 editorial gloss is its own literary note)
- ṣādîq: "righteous" (12:7 in covenant lawsuit context)
- YHWH throughout (not LORD)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(type_, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(type_, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / f'mkt-{type_}' / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

ORIG = {
  "9": {
    "1": "<p>The chapter opens with a genealogy reaching back five generations — Kish son of Abiel son of Zeror son of Bechorath son of Aphiah — before landing on the key descriptor: <em>gibbôr ḥayil</em>, a man of standing/valor. In narrative, genealogies signal that a new major figure is entering the story. The Benjaminite lineage is theologically loaded: Benjamin was the youngest son of Jacob, the tribe nearly exterminated in the Gibeah atrocity (Judg 20), and yet the tribe that will produce Israel's first king.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Saul's introduction is dominated by physical description: <em>bāḥûr wāṭôḇ</em> — choice and good, i.e., a fine young man — and above all his height, for from his shoulders upward he was taller than all the people. The narrative underscores external appearance, which foreshadows the irony to come: YHWH sees differently (16:7). Tall stature was the ANE mark of royal fitness; Saul looks like a king, which is precisely what Israel will point to when affirming him (10:24).</p>",
    "3": "<p>The narrative mechanism that will end with a king being anointed begins with <em>ătōnôt ʾăḇad</em> — donkeys have strayed. Kish sends Saul with a servant to find them. The Hebrew <em>ʾāḇad</em> (strayed/perished) is the same root used for lost sheep and lost children; the narrator's choice of this verb begins the providential-search motif. Israel's future king is on a mundane agricultural errand, unaware that YHWH has already told Samuel to expect him.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The search route — hill country of Ephraim, land of Shalisha, land of Shaalim, land of Benjamin — covers a wide arc of the central highlands without success. The repeated <em>wəlōʾ māṣāʾû</em> (and they did not find them) drives the narrative tension: the more thoroughly the search fails, the more completely Saul is displaced from his starting point. The geography situates the action in the territory between Gibeah (Saul's home) and Ramah (Samuel's base).</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul shows practical wisdom — 'Let us turn back, lest my father stop worrying about the donkeys and worry about us instead.' The inversion is gently ironic: Saul is worried about causing his father anxiety, while YHWH has already arranged the meeting ahead of them. Saul's practical reasoning, pointing homeward, is what YHWH's providence overrides through the servant's suggestion in v6.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The servant knows of a 'man of God' (<em>ʾîš ʾĕlōhîm</em>) in the city — a man of distinction whose every word comes true (<em>ḵol ʾăšer yədabbēr bōʾ yāḇōʾ</em>). This phrase defines the true prophet: words that reliably correspond to reality. The servant's faith, not Saul's initiative, propels the story forward. Samuel has not been named yet — the reader, who already knows Samuel from chs 1-8, recognizes who is being described before the characters do.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul's concern is pragmatic: 'If we go, what shall we bring the man? The bread in our sacks is gone, and there is no gift to bring to the man of God.' The ANE practice of consulting a prophet came with a gift — a fee for prophetic services. Saul's worry reveals he understands the protocol. The problem of having nothing to offer will be resolved by the servant's shekel (v8), but it introduces the theme of what one brings before a holy man.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The servant produces a quarter shekel of silver — enough for a gift. The denominations mentioned here are small; this is not a wealthy consultation. The servant's creative solution moves the narrative: the gift question resolved, the men turn toward the city. Throughout the chapter, the servant functions as the wiser and more spiritually alert companion — he knows about the prophet, has the silver, and suggests the plan.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The narrator inserts an editorial gloss: 'Formerly in Israel, anyone who went to inquire of God said, Come, let us go to the <em>rōʾeh</em> (seer); for the one who is today called a <em>nāḇîʾ</em> (prophet) was formerly called a <em>rōʾeh</em>.' This is a rare instance of the narrative's own historical self-awareness — the writer knows the story is ancient and glosses the archaic title for later readers. The two terms <em>rōʾeh</em> and <em>nāḇîʾ</em> reflect different emphases: <em>rōʾeh</em> stresses the visionary-perceptive function; <em>nāḇîʾ</em> stresses the spokesperson function. Both apply to Samuel.</p>",
    "10": "<p>They go up toward the city. The spatial movement — 'going up' (<em>ʿālāh</em>) — is standard for approaching a higher town, but also carries the cultic connotation of ascending to YHWH (cf. the Psalms of Ascent). They agree to go to the seer. The narrative pacing here is deliberate: each small decision — the servant's knowledge, the gift, the agreement to go — tightens the net of providence without any character realizing it.</p>",
    "11": "<p>At the city's edge they meet young women going out to draw water and ask about the seer. The question is practical, but the women's detailed answer (vv12-13) provides Saul with a precise window: Samuel is here today for the people's sacrifice at the high place, the people won't eat until he blesses it, and he was expected today. The women's knowledge of Samuel's schedule indicates his public visibility and his cultic role presiding over communal sacrificial meals.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The women's reply — 'He is ahead of you; hurry now, for he has come to the city today because the people have a sacrifice today at the high place' — establishes the cultic context. <em>Bāmāh</em> (high place) in this period is not yet condemned as idolatrous; the critique of Solomonic-era high places in Kings does not apply here. Samuel legitimately presides over sacrificial worship at a local high place before the Jerusalem temple exists.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The women specify the timing: the people will not eat until Samuel arrives because he must bless the sacrifice first. This detail places Samuel in the role of sacrificial officiant, a function that will later belong exclusively to priests. In the pre-monarchic and early monarchic period, the boundaries between prophet, priest, and judge overlap; Samuel holds all three functions simultaneously. The instruction to 'go up at once' gives the scene urgency.</p>",
    "14": "<p>As Saul and his servant enter the city, Samuel is coming out toward them on his way up to the high place. The meeting is exactly timed — they arrive at the gate precisely as Samuel exits. The narrative makes no comment; the perfection of the timing is left for the reader to register as the working of divine providence already announced in v15. No one has had to arrange this meeting; YHWH's prior word to Samuel simply proves accurate.</p>",
    "15": "<p>YHWH's disclosure to Samuel the day before: 'Tomorrow about this time I will send you a man from the land of Benjamin, and you shall anoint him as ruler (<em>nāgîd</em>) over my people Israel.' The term <em>nāgîd</em> is significant — it is not <em>melek</em> (king) but the term for a military/political leader designated by divine appointment. <em>Nāgîd</em> in Samuel-Kings regularly describes the one YHWH has chosen ahead of or instead of hereditary kingship. YHWH will anoint a <em>nāgîd</em>, which Israel will call a <em>melek</em> — the tension between divine designation and popular institution is already embedded in the terminology.</p>",
    "16": "<p>YHWH's rationale: 'He shall save my people from the hand of the Philistines. For I have seen my people's misery (<em>kî rāʾîtî ʾeṯ-ʿammî</em>), because their outcry has reached me.' The language is virtually identical to Exodus 3:7-9 — YHWH seeing the people's affliction, hearing their cry, coming down to deliver. The Saul anointing is cast in exodus-deliverance language: this is YHWH again responding to Israel's suffering at the hands of oppressors by raising up a deliverer.</p>",
    "17": "<p>When Samuel sees Saul, YHWH says: 'Here is the man of whom I told you! He it is who shall restrain my people.' <em>Yaʿṣōr bəʿammî</em> — 'restrain/govern my people' — is an unusual phrase, suggesting both military restraint of the enemy and governance of the people. Samuel's recognition is immediate and divine-speech-confirmed: he doesn't need to ask; YHWH narrates in real time as Saul approaches.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Saul approaches Samuel at the gate and asks: 'Tell me where the seer's house is.' He does not yet know he is speaking to the very man he seeks. Samuel's identity is still concealed from Saul — the reader, with Samuel's privilege, knows what Saul does not. This narrative irony (the one sought speaks to the one seeking) is gentle comedy of errors, soon resolved.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Samuel reveals himself: 'I am the seer.' The disclosure is immediate and followed by three commands: go up ahead of me, eat with me today, I will send you on your way tomorrow. Then the news: 'As for your donkeys that were lost three days ago, do not be anxious about them, for they have been found.' The lost-donkey plot is resolved in a single verse — it was never the real story. Saul's mission is complete before he knew he had one.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samuel's rhetorical question to Saul: 'And for whom is all that is desirable in Israel? Is it not for you and for all your father's house?' The phrase 'all that is desirable in Israel' (<em>ûləmî ḵol-ḥemdaṯ yiśrāʾēl</em>) is deliberately ambiguous — it could refer to the kingship or to some unspecified blessing. Saul does not yet understand. This compression — Samuel knows everything, Saul knows nothing — is the chapter's theological point: YHWH's initiative precedes human comprehension.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Saul's response enacts the appropriate humility: 'Am I not a Benjaminite, from the least of the tribes of Israel? And is not my clan the humblest of all the clans of the tribe of Benjamin? Why then have you spoken to me in this way?' The echo of Gideon's self-deprecation (Judg 6:15 — 'my clan is the weakest in Manasseh, and I am the least in my father's house') establishes Saul in the tradition of the unlikely deliverer chosen from the margins. Benjamin's status as 'least' recalls the near-extinction of the tribe in Judges 20-21.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Samuel brings Saul and his servant into the hall and seats them at the head of the invited guests — about thirty men. The seating at the head of the feast honors Saul before the assembled community without yet explaining why. The number thirty suggests a significant gathering, possibly clan leaders or representative elders. The meal before the anointing is itself a covenant-sealing gesture: shared table fellowship precedes the formal appointment.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Samuel commands the cook to bring the portion he had reserved, saying 'Bring the portion I gave you, of which I said to you, Set it aside.' The pre-reserved portion signals advance preparation — Samuel has been expecting this guest. The language is priestly: set-aside portions in cultic meals are portions designated for the officiating priest (cf. Lev 7:34). Samuel is treating Saul's arrival as the fulfillment of a liturgical anticipation.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The cook brings the leg and what is with it and sets it before Saul. Samuel says: 'See, what was kept is set before you. Eat, because until the appointed time it was kept for you when I said, I have invited the people.' The leg (<em>šôq</em>) is the most honored portion of the sacrificial animal, typically given to the priest (cf. Lev 7:32-33). Saul is given the priestly portion without yet being told why — the meal enacts his elevation before the verbal anointing does.</p>",
    "25": "<p>After coming down from the high place, Samuel speaks with Saul on the roof (<em>gāg</em>). Rooftop conversations in Hebrew narrative carry intimacy — the roof is liminal, semi-public, a place for private disclosure above the noise of the street. Samuel communicates something on the roof that the narrative does not reproduce. The content is implied: preparation for the anointing, the shape of his calling, what the morning will bring.</p>",
    "26": "<p>At dawn Samuel calls to Saul on the roof: 'Get up, so that I may send you on your way.' The sending (<em>šālaḥ</em>) echoes the prophetic commissioning vocabulary — Samuel is acting as YHWH's agent dispatching YHWH's appointed. Saul rises and goes out with Samuel. The dawn hour is the hour of prophetic disclosure elsewhere in the Hebrew Bible (cf. Gen 19:15, 22:3).</p>",
    "27": "<p>At the edge of town Samuel tells Saul's servant to pass on ahead while Samuel gives Saul YHWH's word. The deliberate separation — 'stand still for a time, so that I may make known to you the word of God' — creates the private space for the anointing of chapter 10. Samuel orchestrates the encounter with precision, ensuring the anointing happens between them alone. The final verse of ch9 is the threshold moment; ch10 opens on the other side of it.</p>"
  },
  "10": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel takes a flask of oil (<em>pak haššemen</em>), pours it on Saul's head, kisses him, and says: 'Has YHWH not anointed you as ruler (<em>nāgîd</em>) over his heritage (<em>naḥălāṯô</em>)?' The anointing with oil (<em>māšaḥ</em>) is the act that makes Saul <em>māšîaḥ</em> — anointed one. The vocabulary connects to royal and priestly anointing across the Torah and is the root of the later Hebrew <em>māšîaḥ</em> and Greek <em>christos</em>. Samuel's kiss is a covenant gesture — the kiss in the ANE signals the sealing of a relationship, not merely affection. YHWH's heritage is <em>naḥălāh</em> — inheritance/patrimony — Israel seen as YHWH's personal possession.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The first confirming sign: two men at Rachel's tomb in Benjaminite territory at Zelzah will tell Saul the donkeys have been found and that his father is worried about him. Rachel's tomb (near Bethlehem or at Zelzah in Benjamin — the location is debated) is a patriarchal landmark. The sign is mundane and verifiable — Saul can check it immediately. The three signs move from the mundane (donkeys found) to the sacred (Spirit-filled prophecy), scaling up toward the transformative.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The second sign: three men going up to God at Bethel, carrying young goats, three loaves of bread, and a skin of wine. One will greet Saul and give him two loaves of bread, which he will accept. Bethel is a pilgrimage site (one of Israel's major sanctuaries before Jerusalem); the three men are on a cultic journey. Saul receives bread — the provision confirms his appointment. The bread gift anticipates the sacrificial meal at Gibeah, where the Spirit-event will occur.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The men will greet Saul and offer two loaves of bread, which he should accept from them. The dual loaves (<em>šənê leḥem</em>) may echo the double portion of the firstborn or the elevated portion; accepting the gift is an act of receptivity that positions Saul as one who receives provision for the task rather than providing it. The three-sign structure moves incrementally: first domestic news (donkeys), then cultic provision (bread), then prophetic transformation (Spirit).</p>",
    "5": "<p>The third sign: at the hill of God (<em>giḇʿaṯ hāʾĕlōhîm</em>), where the Philistine garrison is, a band of prophets coming down from the high place with harp, tambourine, flute, and lyre, prophesying. The location is charged: the garrison of the Philistine overlords is at the same place where YHWH's prophetic band operates. The juxtaposition — military occupation and prophetic worship in the same location — is the social landscape of early monarchy.</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The Spirit of YHWH will rush upon you (<em>ṣālaḥ</em>), and you will prophesy with them and be turned into another man (<em>wənehepaḵtā ləʾîš ʾaḥēr</em>).' The verb <em>ṣālaḥ</em> denotes a sudden, powerful onset — the same word used when the Spirit came on Samson (Judg 14:6,19; 15:14). The transformation into 'another man' is the most striking phrase: it describes a fundamental reorientation of character, not merely a temporary prophetic episode. This is the OT's language for Spirit-transformation.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'When these signs come to you, do what the occasion requires, for God is with you.' The freedom granted here — 'do what the occasion requires' (<em>ʿăśēh-ləḵā ʾăšer timmāṣēʾ yāḏeḵā</em>, lit. 'do what your hand finds') — is a significant latitude for the newly anointed one. Samuel is not micromanaging; he is authorizing Saul to act with royal initiative once the Spirit confirms the appointment. The formula 'God is with you' is the guarantee that grounds the freedom.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Samuel instructs Saul to go ahead to Gilgal and wait seven days for Samuel to come, offer burnt offerings, and sacrifice peace offerings. This instruction is fateful — Saul's later failure in 13:8-14 occurs precisely when he fails to wait the full seven days. The instruction is both practical (establishing Gilgal as the cultic center for military campaign) and a test: will Saul trust Samuel's timeline when Philistine pressure mounts?</p>",
    "9": "<p>'As he turned his back to leave Samuel, God gave him another heart (<em>wəhāpak-lô ʾĕlōhîm lēḇ ʾaḥēr</em>).' The divine transformation happens immediately at Saul's departure — not at some later date. The 'other heart' corresponds to the 'other man' of v6: both describe the Spirit-effected change that accompanies anointing. All the signs came that day, confirming that Samuel's word was accurate and that divine endorsement was underway.</p>",
    "10": "<p>At Gibeah, the band of prophets meets Saul and the Spirit of God rushes on him (<em>ṣālaḥ</em>), and he prophesies among them. The third sign is fulfilled exactly as Samuel described. Saul is caught up in the prophetic band's Spirit-empowered activity. Prophecy here is not necessarily verbal proclamation; the Hebrew <em>hitnabbēʾ</em> can describe ecstatic behavior, song, and Spirit-inspired movement — a whole-person experience of divine presence.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Those who had known Saul previously see him prophesying among the prophets and say: 'What has happened to the son of Kish? Is Saul also among the prophets (<em>hagam šāʾûl bannəḇîʾîm</em>)?' The question expresses surprise: Saul is not from the prophetic circles, not a trained member of the prophetic band. The Spirit's work exceeds social categories — it falls on a Benjaminite farmer-warrior, not on professional prophets. The question becomes a proverb (see v12).</p>",
    "12": "<p>A man from that area responds: 'And who is their father?' — a rhetorical question implying the prophets have no single parentage, that the Spirit makes prophets without hereditary line. The saying 'Is Saul also among the prophets?' becomes a proverbial expression in Israel, cited again in 19:24. The proverb encodes the lesson: the Spirit moves sovereignly, outside conventional categories of lineage and training.</p>",
    "13": "<p>After the prophetic episode, Saul comes to the high place. The transition back to ordinary movement — from ecstatic Spirit experience to walking up to the high place — marks the temporary nature of this initial Spirit-coming. Unlike the anointing's 'other heart' (v9), the prophetic rush was an episode within a larger process of confirmation, not the permanent Spirit-indwelling of ch 16 which is then definitively withdrawn in 16:14.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Saul's uncle asks him where he went. Saul tells him: he went to look for the donkeys and found them with Samuel. The uncle presses: 'Tell me what Samuel said to you.' The question tests whether Saul will reveal the anointing. His response is instructive.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'Please tell me what Samuel said to you.' The uncle's curiosity is genuine but Saul's discretion in response (v16) is notable. The uncle-nephew relationship was significant in Benjaminite tribal structures; Saul's uncle may have been monitoring family developments.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Saul tells his uncle they found the donkeys — and says nothing about the kingship. 'But about the matter of the kingdom, of which Samuel had spoken, he did not tell him anything.' The restraint is theologically significant: Saul does not yet act on the anointing, does not claim the kingship, does not announce himself. This discretion contrasts with later Saul, who will act precipitously. The concealment preserves YHWH's chosen moment for the public revelation.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Samuel summons the people to YHWH at Mizpah. <em>Mizpah</em> (meaning 'watchtower') in Benjamin was a major assembly point — used for the anti-Benjamin war (Judg 20-21) and now for the formal installation of the king. Samuel convenes the national assembly as YHWH's prophet, giving the event theocratic legitimacy. The choice of Mizpah connects Saul's installation to the site of earlier national crisis.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel's preamble rehearses YHWH's saving acts: 'I brought Israel up from Egypt and delivered you from the hand of the Egyptians and from the hand of all the kingdoms that oppressed you.' The covenant-recital formula before the lot-casting reminds Israel whose authority governs even the selection of a king. The king they are about to install is still YHWH's choice — the lot will confirm it — but YHWH's prior claim as deliverer must be acknowledged first.</p>",
    "19": "<p>'But today you have rejected your God, who saves you from all your evils and your distresses, and you have said to him, Set a king over us.' Samuel's indictment is sharp: the act of asking for a king, even before a king has done anything wrong, is already a rejection of YHWH as king. The people are not rejecting bad leadership; they are rejecting the covenant structure in which YHWH leads through charismatic judges and prophets. Despite this, YHWH concedes the request.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The lot-casting by tribes: Samuel presents all the tribes and Benjamin is chosen. The Hebrew <em>lākaḏ</em> (taken/caught by lot) is used for the lot-selection process — the lot 'takes' the tribe, then the clan, then the household, then the man. This sequential narrowing from tribe to individual enacts YHWH's sovereignty at every level of social organization.</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Matrites are taken from Benjamin, and from the Matrite family Saul son of Kish is taken. But when they seek him, he is not found. Saul hides among the baggage (<em>baḵkēlîm</em>). The image of the king-elect hiding in the luggage is one of the most peculiar in the narrative. Commentators debate whether this is fear, false modesty, or a kind of ritual withdrawal. The hiding emphasizes that Saul is not self-promoting — he must be extracted rather than presenting himself.</p>",
    "22": "<p>They ask YHWH: 'Is there a man still to come here?' YHWH answers: 'He has hidden himself among the baggage.' Even Saul's hiding place is within YHWH's knowledge. The oracle is laconic — no explanation of why Saul hid — but confirms that YHWH's chosen one and the lot-selection agree. The lot is not mechanical chance; it discloses YHWH's predetermined selection.</p>",
    "23": "<p>They run and bring Saul out, and he stands among the people taller than all the people from his shoulders upward — the physical description of 9:2 is repeated. The narrative returns to the height marker at the moment of public presentation: this is the external quality Israel had in mind when they asked for a king 'like all the nations.' YHWH grants them a king who fits their category, knowing the deeper failure that will follow.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Samuel says to all the people: 'Do you see him whom YHWH has chosen? There is none like him among all the people.' And all the people shouted, 'Long live the king!' (<em>yəḥî hammelek</em>). The acclamation formula is the formal public installation. Samuel's rhetorical question — 'Do you see him?' — inverts the seeing-motif: Israel sees the tall external form; YHWH has seen differently. The crowd's unanimous endorsement completes the installation that YHWH's private anointing began.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Samuel explains to the people the rights and duties of the kingship (<em>mišpaṭ hamməlûḵāh</em>), writes them in a scroll, and places it before YHWH. The written record of constitutional limits on kingship is a remarkable act: the monarchy is inaugurated with a constitutional document from the start. This 'law of the king' may be related to Deuteronomy 17:14-20's royal law. Writing it 'before YHWH' (i.e., deposited at the sanctuary) gives it covenant-treaty status.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Saul goes home to Gibeah, and with him go the 'sons of valor' (<em>ḥayil</em>) whose hearts God had touched. The emergence of a voluntary honor guard before any formal military appointment is another sign of divine orchestration: the people who attach themselves to Saul are those whose hearts God has disposed toward him. The kingdom forms organically around the anointed one before any institutional structure is in place.</p>",
    "27": "<p>But some worthless men (<em>bənê bəlîyyaʿal</em>) despise Saul, saying 'How can this man save us?' and bring him no gift. Saul holds his peace. The <em>bənê bəlîyyaʿal</em> — sons of worthlessness/Belial — are the counter-voice in every pivotal moment of the Deuteronomistic History (cf. Judg 19:22; 1 Sam 2:12). Their question — 'How can this man save us?' — is not merely disrespect; it questions the entire enterprise of YHWH's appointed deliverer. Saul's silence in response to mockery contrasts with his later rash reactions.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "1": "<p>Nahash the Ammonite besieges Jabesh-Gilead. Jabesh-Gilead had a complex history with Benjamin: it was the one city that refused to join the anti-Benjamin war (Judg 21:8-9), and its daughters became wives for the Benjaminite survivors. Saul's rescue of Jabesh-Gilead thus has a genealogical dimension — he may be rescuing people connected to his own tribe's survival. Nahash means 'serpent'; the name's ominous resonance with Genesis 3 is not lost in a theologically sensitive reading.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Nahash's terms are brutal: he will make the treaty only if he may gouge out every man's right eye and bring disgrace on all Israel. The gouging of the right eye — the dominant eye for archery and swordsmanship — would permanently disable the men as soldiers. This is not mere cruelty but systematic military neutralization: a blinded right eye removes the city's capacity for armed resistance. The Ammonite king's confidence in his position is total.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The elders of Jabesh buy seven days: 'Leave us alone for seven days so we can send messengers throughout Israel. If there is no one to save us, we will surrender to you.' Nahash agrees — a tactical overconfidence, assuming no one can rally quickly enough. The seven-day window is the narrative opening through which YHWH will act. In a culture without rapid communication, seven days barely suffices for messages to travel and forces to assemble.</p>",
    "4": "<p>When the messengers reach Gibeah of Saul, the people weep. Gibeah is Saul's home city — again the Benjaminite geography creates a personal connection. The messengers have come to the right place without knowing it: the man YHWH has anointed to save Israel is in this very city. The people's weeping is the response of those without a deliverer — the extremity of helplessness that YHWH's Spirit will address in v6.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Saul comes in from the field behind the oxen and asks: 'What is wrong with the people, why are they weeping?' He is still farming — plowing with oxen is significant peasant-king imagery. Saul has not assumed the royal prerogatives of ch 10; he is still a farmer. When they tell him about Jabesh-Gilead, the Spirit intervenes (v6). Saul's return from the field to receive the Spirit parallels Elisha leaving his plowing (1 Kings 19:19-21).</p>",
    "6": "<p>'The Spirit of God rushed upon Saul when he heard these words, and his anger burned greatly.' The formula <em>ṣālaḥ rûaḥ ʾĕlōhîm</em> — the same construction used in the Samson narratives and promised in 10:6 — here combines Spirit-empowerment with righteous indignation (<em>ʾapô bəʾōḏ mĕʾōḏ</em>). The anger is not personal reaction but Spirit-channeled zeal for YHWH's people. The Spirit's coming on Saul at the national crisis confirms the anointing of ch 10 with its first public demonstration.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Saul takes a yoke of oxen, cuts them into pieces, and sends the pieces throughout Israel with the message: 'Whoever does not come after Saul and Samuel, so shall it be done to his oxen.' The action echoes Judges 19:29 where the Levite cut the concubine's body into pieces — both invoke the cut-up body as a summons to tribal assembly. Saul's version is an animal, not a human body, but the symbolic grammar is the same. Adding Samuel's name establishes that Saul acts with prophetic authorization, not merely royal command. The fear of YHWH falls on all the people.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The muster at Bezek yields 300,000 men of Israel and 30,000 men of Judah — the numbers reflect the idealized tribal levy of a united monarchy, not a standing army. The separate count for Judah hints at the north-south distinction that will fracture the kingdom under Rehoboam. Even in Saul's finest hour, the structural fault lines of Israel's eventual division appear in the census data.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The messengers return to Jabesh-Gilead with the news: 'Tomorrow, by the time the sun is hot, you will have deliverance (<em>təšûʿāh</em>).' The word <em>təšûʿāh</em> is YHWH's salvation-word — the same root as Joshua's and Jesus's names. The men of Jabesh rejoice: 'Tomorrow we will come out to you, and you shall do with us whatever seems good to you.' Their surrender-language is now a trust-language; they are no longer surrendering to an enemy but waiting for a deliverer.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The men of Jabesh tell Nahash: 'Tomorrow we will come out to you, and you can do with us whatever seems good to you' — the same words to an enemy as in v9 to the deliverer, but with opposite intent. The deception is defensive necessity: they buy the night so Saul can march. The parallel phrasing (<em>kəṭôḇ bəʿêneḵā</em> to both parties) is the narrator's wry double entendre.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Saul organizes his forces in three companies for a dawn attack and strikes the Ammonites until 'the heat of the day' — fulfilling the timing promised in v9. The three-column attack (a standard ANE tactical formation) routs the Ammonites so completely that those who survive are scattered 'so that no two of them were left together.' The completeness of the victory underscores the Spirit-empowered deliverance; this is not tactical brilliance but theophanic war.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The people ask Samuel: 'Who said Saul should reign over us? Hand those men over so we can kill them.' The worthless men of 10:27 who despised Saul are now subject to popular vindication. The people's demand that the doubters be executed is understandable — the king they despised has just delivered them — but Saul's response is the chapter's moral climax.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Saul says: 'Not a man shall be put to death this day, for today YHWH has worked salvation (<em>təšûʿāh</em>) in Israel.' The mercy-on-a-victory-day is remarkable: the day of military triumph, when the king has maximum authority and popular support, is declared a day of clemency rather than vengeance. Saul explicitly grounds this in YHWH's prior act — 'YHWH has worked salvation' — placing the victory outside his own achievement and therefore the right of revenge outside his prerogative. This is Saul at his best.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Samuel calls all Israel to Gilgal to 'renew the kingdom' (<em>nəḥaddēš hamməlûḵāh</em>). Gilgal was the first campsite after crossing the Jordan (Josh 4-5) — Israel's original covenant-renewal site in the land. The choice of Gilgal for the renewal anchors the new monarchy in the Conquest traditions. The kingship is 'renewed' rather than newly installed, perhaps indicating that the Mizpah installation of ch 10 was conditional pending a victory demonstration.</p>",
    "15": "<p>They make Saul king before YHWH at Gilgal, offer peace offerings (<em>šəlāmîm</em>), and all Israel rejoices greatly. The peace offerings are the covenantal meal that seals the arrangement — after the burnt offering that consecrates the occasion. Saul's kingship is formally installed amid genuine communal celebration, before YHWH, at the most significant covenant site in the land. The chapter ends at the apex of Saul's legitimacy and popular support — the fall of ch 13 will contrast with this height.</p>"
  },
  "12": {
    "1": "<p>Samuel's farewell speech begins with a public accountability review: 'I have listened to you in all that you have said to me and have set a king over you.' Samuel acknowledges his compliance with the people's demand — he is not revisiting the question of whether the kingship was right but moving to the terms of accountability that now govern it. The speech functions as a covenant lawsuit (<em>rîḇ</em>) — a juridical form used when YHWH or his representative brings charges against the covenant people.</p>",
    "2": "<p>'Now behold, the king walks before you, and I am old and gray, and behold, my sons are with you. I have walked before you from my youth until this day.' Samuel's intergenerational framing — the king is young and beginning, Samuel is old and ending — establishes the transition moment. His sons' presence in the assembly is a loaded reference: they were the corrupt judges of 8:1-3 whose failure precipitated the demand for a king. Samuel does not hide this history.</p>",
    "3": "<p>'Here I am; testify against me before YHWH and before his anointed. Whose ox have I taken? Whose donkey have I taken? Whom have I defrauded? Whom have I oppressed? From whose hand have I taken a bribe to blind my eyes with it?' The rhetorical questions constitute a covenant integrity oath — Samuel invokes YHWH and the king as witnesses to his clean record. The specific items (ox, donkey, bribe) correspond to the abuses Samuel will soon describe as the pattern of kings (8:14-17). Samuel's governance was the alternative to what kings do.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The people respond: 'You have not defrauded us or oppressed us or taken anything from any man's hand.' The unanimous public acquittal is Samuel's covenant credential — he exercised authority without extracting tribute. The contrast with the corrupt sons of 8:3 and the projected abuses of royal government (8:11-18) is pointed. The people's verdict legitimizes Samuel's authority to now speak covenant law to them.</p>",
    "5": "<p>'YHWH is witness against you, and his anointed is witness this day, that you have not found anything in my hand.' And they said, 'He is witness.' The double-witness formula (YHWH + the king) satisfies Deuteronomy's requirement for two or three witnesses (Deut 19:15). Samuel has established the court's legitimacy before delivering the covenant address.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Samuel continues: 'YHWH is witness, who appointed Moses and Aaron and who brought your fathers up from the land of Egypt.' The saving-history section (vv6-13) begins with the Exodus — the founding act of covenant relationship. Samuel's survey will move from Moses/Aaron through the judges to the present, building the case that YHWH has been Israel's constant deliverer while Israel has been a constant covenant-breaker.</p>",
    "7": "<p>'Now therefore stand still so that I may plead with you before YHWH concerning all the righteous deeds (<em>ṣidqôṯ</em>) of YHWH that he did for you and for your fathers.' <em>Ṣidqôṯ YHWH</em> — YHWH's righteous acts/saving acts — is a technical term in the Psalms and prophets for YHWH's interventions on behalf of the covenant people. Samuel frames YHWH's history as a record of consistent faithfulness; he will then frame Israel's history as a record of consistent apostasy. The contrast is the foundation of the covenant lawsuit.</p>",
    "8": "<p>'When Jacob went into Egypt and your fathers cried out to YHWH, then YHWH sent Moses and Aaron, who brought your fathers out of Egypt and made them dwell in this place.' The saving-history summary compresses Exodus through Settlement into a single verse — the characteristic Deuteronomistic credo form (cf. Deut 26:5-9; Josh 24:2-13). The credo functions as covenant memory: this is what YHWH did, which is why covenant obligation exists.</p>",
    "9": "<p>But they forgot YHWH their God, and he sold them into the hand of Sisera the commander of Jabin's army and into the hand of the Philistines and into the hand of the king of Moab. The <em>šāḵaḥ</em> (forget) of covenant unfaithfulness is paired with <em>mākar</em> (sold/delivered over) — YHWH's judicial abandonment of the people to their enemies is the consequence of forgetting him. The three oppressors listed (Sisera, Philistines, Moab) cover major episodes of the book of Judges.</p>",
    "10": "<p>They cried out to YHWH: 'We have sinned, because we have forsaken YHWH and served the Baals and the Ashtaroth. Now deliver us from the hand of our enemies and we will serve you.' The covenant repentance formula is identical to the cycle pattern in Judges (e.g., Judg 10:10-16): acknowledgment of sin, identification of the sin (serving Baals and Ashtaroth), petition for deliverance, pledge of renewed service. Samuel is identifying the present moment as yet another instance of the recurring cycle.</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH sent Jerubbaal (Gideon), Bedan, Jephthah, and Samuel himself to deliver Israel. The list of judges includes 'Bedan' — an otherwise unknown figure; some manuscripts read 'Barak' here (cf. LXX). Samuel's inclusion of himself in the list of deliverers is not self-aggrandizement but covenantal continuity: his office is in the same sequence as the judges, the last expression of the charismatic-deliverer pattern before the monarchy.</p>",
    "12": "<p>'And when you saw that Nahash the king of the Ammonites came against you, you said to me, No, but a king shall reign over us, when YHWH your God was your king.' The juxtaposition is sharp: the Ammonite threat (just resolved in ch 11) was the stated reason for demanding a king. But YHWH was already their king, and the judges-pattern of deliverance was still operative. Israel's demand was not practical necessity but an act of covenant rejection.</p>",
    "13": "<p>'And now behold the king whom you have chosen, for whom you have asked; behold, YHWH has set a king over you.' The double <em>hinnēh</em> (behold) and the double acknowledgment — you chose/you asked — holds the people accountable while affirming that YHWH has fulfilled the request. The king they wanted is now their king; YHWH has conceded while maintaining the record of the demand's faithlessness. The tension between divine disapproval and divine concession is unresolved — it characterizes the entire monarchic history.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The conditional covenant formula: 'If you will fear YHWH and serve him and obey his voice and not rebel against the commandment of YHWH, and if both you and the king who reigns over you will follow YHWH your God, it will be well.' The introduction of the king into the covenant formula is the new element: monarchy does not replace the Sinai covenant but is incorporated under it. Both people and king are now equally subject to covenant obligation. The blessing-conditional is open: the monarchy can still succeed if covenant faithfulness is maintained.</p>",
    "15": "<p>'But if you will not obey the voice of YHWH and will rebel against the commandment of YHWH, then the hand of YHWH will be against you and your king.' The curse-conditional mirrors the blessing but adds 'and your king' — the monarchy participates in the covenant curse as well as the blessing. This is the theological framework for every subsequent royal evaluation in Samuel-Kings: kings are judged by covenant faithfulness, and the people's fate is tied to their king's obedience.</p>",
    "16": "<p>'Now therefore stand and see this great thing that YHWH will do before your eyes.' Samuel invites the assembled Israel to witness a covenant sign. The invitation to 'stand and see' (<em>hiṯyaṣṣəḇû ûrəʾû</em>) is a theophanic summons — the language used when YHWH is about to act visibly. The covenant sign will be thunder and rain (v17-18) — unusual weather at wheat harvest, which occurs in the dry season (May-June) when rain is abnormal in Palestine.</p>",
    "17": "<p>'Is it not wheat harvest today? I will call upon YHWH, that he may send thunder and rain. And you shall know and see that your wickedness is great, which you have done in the sight of YHWH, in asking for yourselves a king.' The thunder-at-harvest is a meteorological sign of divine displeasure: wheat harvest in ancient Canaan/Israel falls in May-June during the dry season; unseasonal rain and thunder would be unmistakable as a divine message. Samuel's ability to summon such a sign confirms his prophetic authority.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Samuel calls on YHWH, and YHWH sends thunder and rain that day. The entire people greatly fears YHWH and Samuel. The combined fear of YHWH and Samuel indicates that the sign achieved its purpose: the people recognize both divine reality and prophetic authority in a single event. The thunder-and-rain sign is the covenant lawsuit's climactic 'exhibit': YHWH testifies in the natural world.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The people say to Samuel: 'Pray for your servants to YHWH your God, that we may not die, for we have added to all our sins this evil, to ask for ourselves a king.' The combination of awe and self-condemnation is the desired covenant response — they acknowledge the sin, not merely the fear. Their appeal to Samuel's intercession ('pray for your servants') acknowledges that they need a mediator whose relationship with YHWH can withstand their guilt. The phrase 'we have added to all our sins this evil' is covenant self-indictment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Samuel's consolation: 'Do not be afraid; you have done all this evil. Yet do not turn aside from following YHWH, but serve YHWH with all your heart.' The pastoral grace of this verse is extraordinary: Samuel does not minimize the sin ('you have done all this evil') but immediately pivots to the path forward. The covenant's conditional threats do not preclude continued covenant relationship; repentance and ongoing service are still available. Fear is not the goal; covenant faithfulness is.</p>",
    "21": "<p>'And do not turn aside after empty things (<em>haṯṯōhû</em>) that cannot profit or deliver, for they are empty.' <em>Tōhû</em> — void, emptiness, the word used in Genesis 1:2 for formless creation — describes the idols and political alternatives that Israel might pursue. The contrast between YHWH who delivers and the <em>tōhû</em>-things that cannot is Samuel's final anti-idolatry warning. The word that described pre-creation emptiness describes the religious alternatives to YHWH.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'For YHWH will not abandon his people, for his great name's sake, because it has pleased YHWH to make you a people for himself.' The ground of covenant security is entirely YHWH's self-commitment: not Israel's merit, not the monarchy's strength, but YHWH's own name (<em>šəmô haggāḏôl</em>) and his pleasure (<em>hôʾîl YHWH</em>) in making Israel his people. The double grounding — name and pleasure — is the irreversible foundation. YHWH's reputation is at stake in Israel's survival; he cannot abandon his people without abandoning his own identity.</p>",
    "23": "<p>'Moreover, as for me, far be it from me that I should sin against YHWH by ceasing to pray for you, and I will instruct you in the good and the right way.' Samuel's pledge of continued intercession is his covenant commitment: even in retirement from the judgeship, he will not withdraw prayer. To 'cease to pray' (<em>ḥāḏal mippallēl</em>) is declared a sin against YHWH — prayer for the people is a covenant obligation, not an optional pastoral extra. Samuel's identity as prophet-intercessor will persist beyond political power.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'Only fear YHWH and serve him faithfully with all your heart, for consider what great things he has done for you.' The closing call synthesizes the entire speech: covenant fear, covenant service, whole-hearted devotion, grounded in grateful memory of YHWH's saving acts. The <em>rāʾû</em> (see/consider) returns to the eyewitness theme — they have just seen YHWH act in thunder and rain; let them see the full scope of his saving history and respond accordingly.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'But if you still do wickedly, you shall be swept away, both you and your king.' The speech ends with the curse-conditional in its starkest form — 'swept away' (<em>tîssāpû</em>) — and includes the king in the potential catastrophe. The final verse is the prophecy of the monarchy's potential failure before the monarchy has ruled a year. The book of Samuel will take the rest of its pages demonstrating that this warning was not heeded, and that even the best of Israel's kings — David — falls into the wickedness that leads toward the sweep.</p>"
  }
}

